                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Memory Flux (or any of the other mem blur spells) are your only method to clear mob aggro entirely (apart from COH/logging/zoning) - boggle is just an aggro reducer, but since it is a detrimental spell, you get 1pt of hate from it (which is why it's such a great pulling spell - 1st hit from the tank gets aggro).
<br />

<br />
One sure way to tell if a mob is blurred when mezzed is by watching it's health bar - when the blur sticks, it will regen to full in a tic or two if it's damaged.  If the mob is undamaged, *sometimes* /assist on it will give you a clue if it still is aggrod on someone, but sometimes the mob retains its old targeting even if it no longer has aggro so this isn't 100%.
<br />

<br />
I'm not sure if this still works, but at one time you could also use invis to check aggro - if the mob wasn't see invis, that is.  Mez, blur then invis and con the mob and if it kept scowling at you, you still had aggro.  This might have been changed tho, so you'd need to try it out to see if it still works.
<br />

<br />
Your best bet is to mez it, blur it a few times and then drop paci on it before the mez drops - if you time it right, the mob should path home and not re-aggro you.  IIRC the mobs in those expds have pretty large aggro radii, so you might blur it successfully and just have it re-aggro on you from proximity when mez breaks if you are too close.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
