                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">One sure way to tell if a mob is blurred when mezzed is by watching it's health bar - when the blur sticks, it will regen to full in a tic or two if it's damaged. If the mob is undamaged, *sometimes* /assist on it will give you a clue if it still is aggrod on someone, but sometimes the mob retains its old targeting even if it no longer has aggro so this isn't 100%.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Mezzed mob target updates do not happen -- if they do, they are once in a purple pokadoted moon.
<br />

<br />
There are a few ways.
<br />

<br />
1&gt; Boggle a bunch.  2 bogges per debuff spell.  Slow + mez + tash = 6 boggles.
<br />
2&gt; If the pet is higher level than the NPC, make sure the mage has /pet taunt on.  A successful taunt helps.
<br />
3&gt; Root.  Until a DD break sit.
<br />
4&gt; Mem blurs.  Blanket of Forgetfulness seems to be the most reliable.  Mem blurs are all or nothing.
<br />
5&gt; Snare+kite.  Nothing wrong with aggro kiting!  Eventually the pet will outaggro.
<br />

<br />
I would advise spending 3 AA on EF 1.  It seems to help.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
